      "_id": "21",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "This is what google says The right-angle theorem typically refers to the Pythagorean Theorem (\\(a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}\\)), which states that in a right-angled triangle, the square of the hypotenuse (the side opposite the right angle) is equal to the sum of the squares of the other two sides (legs). The theorem can also refer to the condition that if the sum of the squares of two sides of a triangle equals the square of the third side, then the angle opposite the third side is a right angle.",
